@node whatis "Shades.guide v1.5"

   What is Shades?


   @{i}Do you recognise this?@{ui}

   You have this perfect monitor with your Amiga, with all
   the controls you'll ever need. Except one: sunlight control.
   You find yourself constantly adjusting the contrast setting
   of your monitor because:
   - the sunlight in your room just got brighter or dimmer
   - you started a program with a very light or very dark
     background color 
   - both of the above happened.

   There are several solutions to this problem:
   1. You can sit in a dark room and grow mushrooms 
   2. Don't start programs with a very light or very dark
      background color
   3. Build an SLCD (Solar Light Control Device)

   Tried it all, didn't work.

   So finally, I wrote Shades: a program to lighten or darken
   any (background) color of any screen.

   It's a commodity, it has a hotkey sequence (definable
   through tooltypes), you can set different light/dim values
   for different screens and it will remember those settings
   (until you switch of your Amiga, that is).

   There is another use for Shades as well!
   Some programs use the wrong color pen for text output (so you
   get lightgreen text on a lightgrey background). 
   With Shades you can darken that pen to a more readable color.


   Read on @{" What it is not! " link whatisnot}
@endnode

@node whatisnot "Shades.guide v1.5"

   What is Shades not!


   1. It is @{fg highlight}not@{fg text} a palette tool. If you need to change screen colors,
      you need another program. Shades will however recognise any 
      'alien' changes in the palette and adjust itself to it.

   2. It is not free: it's @{" FlyWare " link flyware}!


   Read on @{" System requirements " link whatyouneed}
@endnode

@node whatyouneed "Shades.guide v1.5"

   System requirements


   Shades will only work on an Amiga.
   Shades requires AmigaDOS 2.0 and above.
   Shades requires the ReqTools.library © Nico Francois.
   It does not need the AGA chipset.


   Read on @{" Starting Shades " link starting}
@endnode

@node starting "Shades.guide v1.5"

   Starting Shades


   Just double-click on the Shades icon. If Shades is already loaded,
   the resident version will be started and/or popped to front.

   If you like Shades to start every time you (re)boot your machine,
   just drop it into your SYS:WBStartup drawer.
   All the @{" Tooltypes " link tooltypes} are set for automatic startup.

   If it is already loaded into memory, you can pop it up
   with a hotkey sequence (default: ctrl alt =).
   Shades will open a window on the front screen, automatically
   adjusting itself to the screen type and number of colors.


   Read on @{" Operating Shades " link operation}
@endnode


@node operation "Shades.guide v1.5"

   Operating Shades


   Shades is controlled by two gadgets: a palette gadget and a slider gadget.

   _____________________________________
   @{bg shine}[.] Shades v1.5                  [][]@{bg back}
   -------------------------------------
   | _________________________________ |
   | |       |       |       |       | |
   | |       |       |       |       | |
   | |       |       |       |       | |
   | |       |       |       |       | |
   | |_______|_______|_______|_______| |
   |               __________________  |
   | Dim amount 0 @{bg back}[______[@{bg shine}___@{bg back}]_______] |
   |___________________________________|


   1. Color palette

      Click one of the colors to select the screen color to dim
      or lighten. This color defaults to the first one: the perfect
      color for most programs.
      The number of selectable colors is dynamicly changed to the
      maximum number the current screen uses.

   2. Dim Amount slider - marked Dim amount
      Use this to lighten or darken the color you have choosen with
      the Color palette gadget. Values lay between -5/+5 units.
      One or two steps plus or minus are sufficient in most cases.

   Shades will remember the dim/lighten factor of a screen, so if you
   hide it and pop it up again, it will restore the Dim Amount value to
   the size you set.

   @{fg highlight}Note@{fg text} If you select another color, the Dim amount value of the
   previous selected color will be reset to 0! You can only change
   one color at a time (it's not a palette tool, you see).

   Shades has a menu too! The three items are:

   About... R-Amiga Shift ?   Info about Shades
   Hide     R-Amiga h         Hide Shade; unhide it with the hotkey
   Quit     R-Amiga q         You will be asked for confirmation

   @{fg highlight}Note@{fg text} Shades will @{i}not@{ui} reset the screen colors when you quit!
   If you @{i}re@{ui}start it, Shades will use the current screen colors as its 
   default color values.


   Read on @{" Icon & Tooltypes " link tooltypes}
@endnode

@node tooltypes "Shades.guide v1.5"

   Icon & tooltypes


   Shades has a NewIcon icon and a Magic WorkBench icon.

   Available tooltypes are:

   DONOTWAIT, CX_PRIORITY=0
   Both needed by Commodity Exchange: don't mess with these two.

   CX_POPUP=NO
   YES   if you want Shades to show up every time you (re)bootstart it
   NO    if you want it to start hidden

   HOTKEY=ctrl alt =
   The key sequence@{fg highlight}*@{fg text} to pop up Shades: defaults to 'ctrl alt ='

 @{fg highlight}*@{fg text} The =-character resembles window shades/blinds the most, I think.

   NAME=Shades
   The Commodities Exchange program uses this name to identify
   Shades. In rare cases this might conflict with a program
   that uses the same name. If so, change this to something else.


   Read on @{" Trouble shooting " link troubleshooting}
@endnode

@node troubleshooting "Shades.guide v1.5"

   Troubleshooting


   Q: When I start Shades, nothing happens!
   A: It starts without popping up! Solution:
      Hit "ctrl alt =" or use the Commodity Exchange program to pop it up.
      See also @{" tooltype CX_POPUP " link tooltypes}.

   Q: When I start Shades, a requester pops up telling me that
      Shades is already running. But I'm sure it is not!
   A: There is probably another commodity running that uses the
      same name Shades does to identify itself to the Commodity
      Exchange program. Solution: see @{" tooltype NAME " link tooltypes}.

   Q: I slide up the Dim amount slider to the max/min, but nothing 
      seems to happen.
   A: You are changing the wrong color.
      Shades remembers the color you have changed. The palette gadget does not
      `highlight' this color though (should be implemented in the next version!)
      Click in the palette gadget to select the color to change @{fg highlight}or@{fg text}
   A: Shades calculates its dim factor using RGB values. If one
      of these (Red, Green or Blue) reaches its maximum or minimum
      value, Shades stops dimming in order to preserve the original
      color.

   Q: I don't have a clue what to send you as a @{" FlyWare " link flyware} contribution.
   A: Send me US$5. I'll think of something ;)


   Read on @{" It's Flyware! " link flyware}
@endnode

@node flyware "Shades.guide v1.5"

   FlyWare?!


   Yeah, well, uhhh: I collect anything that has to do with
   flying, see.

   I have metal cast models, books, pins, bears in pilot suits,
   ties & underwear with planes, clocks, toys,
   santa-claus-in-a-plane, jigsaw puzzles, an airplane-telephone, 
   all kinds of cartoon-figures-in-a-plane, a front tire of
   a Boeing 727 & lots more.
   My Amiga is probably the only one in this galaxy with an
   airplane-formed pointer.
   Oh yeah: I am a paraglider pilot as well.


   @{fg highlight}So, here's the deal.@{fg text}

   If you use Shades, please send me something `airplanish': 
   see the list above to get an idea.

   Send your FlyWare contribution to the @{" Author " link author}.


   Read on @{" Credits & Legal Stuff " link legalstuff}
@endnode

